.TH GIT-STAGE-BATCH 1 "May 2026" "git-stage-batch @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-stage-batch \- hunk-by-hunk and line-by-line staging for git
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git-stage-batch
[\fB\-C\fR \fIPATH\fR] [\fB\-i\fR] [\fB\-\-version\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B git-stage-batch
provides a command-oriented workflow for reviewing and staging git changes.
It presents hunks, files, and batches as numbered review targets so changes
can be included, skipped, discarded, saved for later, or moved between batches.
.PP
State is maintained under
.BR .git/git-stage-batch/ .
Sessions can be stopped, resumed, undone, or redone while preserving enough
state to keep later commands tied to the selected review.
.SH HELP
The top-level help is an overview. Each public subcommand has its own manual
page. For example:
.RS
.nf
git-stage-batch include --help
git help stage-batch-include
.fi
.RE
.SH COMMON WORKFLOW
.TP
.B git-stage-batch start
Start a review session and select the first hunk.
.TP
.B git-stage-batch show
Show the selected hunk or open a file review.
.TP
.B git-stage-batch include
Stage the selected hunk.
.TP
.B git-stage-batch skip
Leave the selected hunk for a later pass.
.TP
.B git-stage-batch discard
Remove the selected hunk from the working tree.
.TP
.B git-stage-batch again
Start another pass over skipped hunks.
.TP
.B git-stage-batch stop
Clear session state.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Session Commands
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-start (1)
Start a new hunk review session.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-show (1)
Show the selected hunk, a file review, or a batch review.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-status (1)
Show current session progress.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-again (1)
Start a new pass over skipped hunks.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-stop (1)
Stop the current session.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-abort (1)
Undo all changes made during the session.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-undo (1)
Undo the most recent undoable session operation.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-redo (1)
Redo the most recently undone session operation.
.SS Change Commands
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-include (1)
Stage selected changes, save them to a batch, or apply batch changes to the
index.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-skip (1)
Mark selected live changes as skipped.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-discard (1)
Remove live changes, save them to a batch, or reverse batch changes.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-apply (1)
Apply batch changes to the working tree without staging them.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-reset (1)
Remove selected lines from a batch's record without changing the working tree.
.SS Batch Commands
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-new (1)
Create a named batch.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-list (1)
List batches.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-drop (1)
Delete a batch.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-annotate (1)
Set a batch note.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-sift (1)
Remove already-present changes from a batch.
.SS Other Commands
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-interactive (1)
Run the continuous interactive interface.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-block-file (1)
Permanently exclude a file from future sessions.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-unblock-file (1)
Allow a blocked file to be reviewed again.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-suggest-fixup (1)
Suggest a commit to fix up with the selected hunk.
.TP
.BR git-stage-batch-install-assets (1)
Install bundled assistant assets into the repository.
.SH LINE IDS
Line-oriented commands accept comma-separated IDs and ranges such as
.BR 1 ,
.BR 1,3,5 ,
or
.BR 1,3,5-7 .
Displayed IDs are review IDs, not necessarily source file line numbers.
.SH FILE SCOPES
Commands that accept
.B \-\-file
may take a path or may omit the path to use the selected file. Commands that
accept
.B \-\-files
resolve gitignore-style patterns, including ordered
.B !
exclusions, to one or more changed files.
.SH AUTOMATIC HUNK SELECTION
Hunk actions normally select and display the next hunk after they complete.
Use
.B \-\-no\-auto\-advance
on an action command to leave no hunk selected. Use
.B \-\-auto\-advance
to opt back in for one command. The
.B start
and
.B again
commands can set the session default.
.SH BATCHES
Batches are named collections of changes stored under git refs. They allow
changes to be saved, reapplied, discarded, reset, or transformed later.
Most users can use
.BR include ,
.BR skip ,
and
.BR discard
without using batches.
